aws::graph::propositions: # Experimental Amateur Built Corben Baby Ace Aircraft Accident Information
The aircraft involved was an experimental amateur built Corben Baby Ace with registration N3RH.
The accident occurred on October 5, 2014, at approximately 1215 Pacific daylight time.
The accident occurred shortly after takeoff from Lincoln Regional Airport in Lincoln, California.
Lincoln Regional Airport has the identifier LHM.
The aircraft was registered to the pilot.
The aircraft was operated by the pilot under the provisions of Title 14 Code of Federal Regulations Part 91.
The pilot held a private pilot license.
The pilot was the sole occupant of the aircraft.
The pilot was not injured in the accident.
Visual meteorological conditions prevailed at the time of the accident.
No flight plan was filed for the personal flight.
The local flight originated from Lincoln Regional Airport about 5 minutes prior to the accident.
The pilot departed from runway 15.
The pilot flew straight out to about 1,000 feet above ground level.
The engine began to sputter at approximately 1,000 feet above ground level.
The pilot initiated a 180-degree turn toward the airport.
The pilot did not have enough altitude to reach the airport.
The pilot initiated a forced landing to a nearby field.
During the off-airport landing, the landing gear collapsed.
The aircraft subsequently nosed over after the landing gear collapsed.
The fuselage was structurally damaged.
The engine firewall was structurally damaged.
The aircraft was recovered to a secure location for further examination.
The wings were removed to facilitate recovery of the aircraft.
The aircraft had a Continental C75-12 engine.
The Continental C75-12 engine had serial number 179612.
The engine remained attached to the airframe.
All engine accessories remained attached with the exception of the carburetor.
The carburetor was displaced from its mounts.
The top spark plugs were removed during examination.
The crankshaft was rotated by hand using the propeller during examination.
Thumb compression was obtained on all four cylinders during examination.
Both magnetos produced spark with impulse coupling engagement when the crankshaft was rotated.
The carburetor was intact despite being separated from its mounts.
The National Transportation Safety Board (NTSB) investigated the accident.
The pilot provided a written statement to the National Transportation Safety Board investigator-in-charge.

text:
# Factual Information

## History of Flight

| | |
| --- | --- |
| Enroute-cruise | Loss of engine power (total) |
| Landing-landing roll | Off-field or emergency landing |
| Landing-landing roll | Nose over/nose down (Defining event) |

On October 5, 2014, about 1215 Pacific daylight time, an experimental amateur built Corben Baby Ace, N3RH, was substantially damaged during a forced landing shortly after takeoff from the Lincoln Regional Airport (LHM), Lincoln, California. The airplane was registered to and operated by the pilot under the provisions of Title 14 Code of Federal Regulations Part 91. The private pilot, sole occupant of the airplane, was not injured. Visual meteorological conditions prevailed and no flight plan was filed for the personal flight. The local flight originated from LHM about 5 minutes prior to the accident.

In a written statement to the National Transportation Safety Board (NTSB) investigator-in-charge (IIC), the pilot reported that he departed runway 15 and flew straight out to about 1,000 feet above ground level (agl) when the engine began to sputter. The pilot stated that he initiated a 180-degree turn toward the airport, however, did not have enough altitude to make the airport and initiated a forced landing to a nearby field. During the off-airport landing, the landing gear collapsed and the airplane subsequently nosed over.

Examination of the airplane by the NTSB IIC revealed that the fuselage and engine firewall was structurally damaged. The airplane was recovered to a secure location for further examination.

Examination of the recovered airplane revealed that the wings were removed to facilitate recovery of the airplane. The Continental C75-12 engine, serial number 179612, remained attached to the airframe. All engine accessories remained attached with the exception of the carburetor, which was displaced from its mounts. The top spark plugs were removed and the crankshaft was rotated by hand using the propeller. Thumb compression was obtained on all four cylinders. Both magnetos produced spark with impulse coupling engagement when the crankshaft was rotated.

The carburetor was intact, however, separated from its mounts.
